        "content": "<p>I want to submit to you the following shenanigan which I find very funny to play with.</p>\n<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi>Y</mi><mi>o</mi></msup><mo>×</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p  : Y^o\\times Y\\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> be an endoprofunctor on a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>. Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> a set, and denote still as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> the costant functor at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> is an <em>eigenvalue</em> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> if the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(p/\\Lambda)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord\">/Λ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of natural transformations <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p \\Rightarrow \\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> is nonempty and... something else I'd like to figure out so that what follows makes sense (and avoids vacuous truths of sort).</li>\n<li>A functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F : Y^{op}\\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> is an <em>eigenvector</em> wrt <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> if, when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> is an eigenvalue, for every <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p\\Rightarrow\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(p/\\Lambda)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord\">/Λ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, there is an initial cowedge <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>×</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p(x,y)\\times Fy \\to \\Lambda\\times Fx</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> (so that the \"matrix product\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mo>∫</mo><mi>y</mi></msup><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>×</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(p\\otimes F)x:= \\int^y p(x,y)\\times Fy</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1654em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8593em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.2579em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> between the matrix <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> and the vector <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is canonically isomorphic to the product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda\\times F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> of the \"scalar\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> and of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>, evaluated at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>, as prescribed by the theory of eigenvalues/eigenvectors).</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 513283709,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1745163003
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have a hunch that connectedness, or some sort of contractibility, of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(p/\\Lambda)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord\">/Λ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> could be required; I also suspect the second property is too strong, but note that (for example) with this definition the eigenspace of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> (the subcategory spanned by all eigenvectors wrt <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span>) is closed under colimits, so it can't be too trivial a subcategory of the small-cocomplete category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[Y^{op},Set]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>. Note also that the only eigenvector of hom is the terminal object, with eigenspace the whole category, as god intended.</p>",
        "id": 513284009,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1745163208
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I remember a few people that, like me, love categorifying linear algebra; <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276935\">@Simon Willerton</span> might have tinkered with this idea, or maybe <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276037\">@Jade Master</span> (who I remember was blogging about the analogies between matrices and quantale-enriched profunctors?)</p>",
        "id": 513284160,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1745163301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you have examples to aid intuition on what these look like?</p>",
        "id": 515264533,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1746008858
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, if you squint your eyes a profunctor is a matrix.. and the coend computation yields almost instantaneosuly that if a profunctor results as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p=L\\times R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> for a copresheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> and a presheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> has eigenvalue the functor tensor product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mo>∫</mo><mi>x</mi></msup><mi>L</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>R</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L\\otimes R=\\int^x Lx\\times Rx</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1654em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8593em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.2579em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Lx</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>, with associated eigenvector <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Compare with the analogue fact of life, that if a matrix <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> results as the tensor product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">v\\otimes w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">v</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span></span></span></span>, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> has the dot product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">v\\cdot w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">v</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span></span></span></span> as eigenvalue, and eigenspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟨</mo><mi>v</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟩</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\langle v\\rangle</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">⟨</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">v</span><span class=\"mclose\">⟩</span></span></span></span> (the other eigenvalue is 0, with eigenspace an orthogonal complement of v... that's more difficult to categorify).</p>",
        "id": 515284202,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1746014421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have a list, now more abundant than days ago, of similar analogies. So, this problem ended up being so pretty it can be its own motivation -and I see only one path to aid intuition: trust the coends you write, and see what comes out of them.</p>",
        "id": 515284448,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1746014469
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wonder if working with spans of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty\\rm Grpd</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Grpd</span></span></span></span></span> as in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1602.05082\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1602.05082</a> might make the analogies smoother</p>",
        "id": 515366446,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1746035718
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably a distraction, but since <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> brought up that paper, 'Homotopical Linear Algebra',  something I meant to return to was a couple of long comments made by Joachim Kock on the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-Category Café, <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2021/06/schur_functors_and_categorifie.html#c059869\">here</a>, which passed seemingly unobserved.</p>\n<p>Wherever I read Joachim, he seems to be pushing things in a homotopical direction. E.g., there's talk of some unavoidable 'homotopy overhead' in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.05108\">Whole-grain Petri nets and processes</a>:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ShWpfnqXxrbyV8b0lyleqJhX/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ShWpfnqXxrbyV8b0lyleqJhX/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"723x195\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/ShWpfnqXxrbyV8b0lyleqJhX/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>Then back <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2013/12/commuting_limits_and_colimits.html#c045378\">here</a>, he jumps in quickly to support a hunch I'd had on some result Tom Leinster was airing on commuting limits and colimits over groups.</p>",
        "id": 515479099,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1746093986
    }
]